19. Git Export: Commit tree JSONs to a remote git repo from inside the app. [STATUS: COMPLETE]
Users should be able to push tree JSON exports to a separate remote git repo directly from the UI.

Setup (via .env):
- OST_USER_NAME — display name for git commit author
- OST_USER_EMAIL — email for git commit author
- GIT_TOKEN — optional, for HTTPS auth (needed in Docker / clean VMs; not needed if VM already has git auth)
- GIT_REMOTE_URL — remote repo URL (e.g. git@github.com:myorg/ost-trees.git)
- GIT_BRANCH — branch to commit to (default: main)

UX flow:
- "Commit to Git" button in the UI (exact placement TBD)
- Dialog with commit message textarea
- Backend exports tree JSON, writes to local clone at ~/.ost-app/git-repos/{slug}/
- File path: {project-name}/{tree-name}.json (auto-derived)
- Runs: git pull --rebase, git add, git commit --author="Name <email>", git push
- On push conflict: retry once (pull --rebase + push). If still fails, abort and show error.

Safety rules:
- NEVER git push --force
- NEVER auto-resolve merge conflicts
- Fail loudly on unexpected state
- Commits are always additive

Auth strategy:
- If GIT_TOKEN env var is set, rewrite remote URL to https://{token}@host/path.git
- Otherwise use system git auth as-is (SSH keys, credential helpers)

No user management — identity comes from .env fields. Each user has their own VM + .env.

